1.1.1 These results are post-stratified to gaming populations by country/age/gender

# create an example dataframe
label <- "stylized"
game <- "Grand Theft Auto V"
example.df <- long.df %>% filter(label=={{label}} & game=={{game}})

# build the model currently lm model, change the predictors as needed
model <- glm(answer ~ gender + ageCut + country, data = example.df, family=binomial(link="logit"))

# predict value based on the model
# ground.truth$estimate <- model %>% predict(newdata = ground.truth, type="response")
# post <- ground.truth %>% mutate(predict_prop = estimate*UserCount.per)
plot.post <- function(d) {
  ground.truth <- ground.truth %>% group_by_at(d) %>%
    mutate(population=sum(UserCount, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(UserCount.per=UserCount/population) %>% select(-population)
  
  ground.truth$estimate <- model %>% predict(newdata = ground.truth, type="response")
  post <- ground.truth %>% mutate(predict_prop = estimate*UserCount.per)
  post$demo <- post[[d]]
  post <- post %>%
    group_by(demo) %>% 
    summarise(lm = sum(predict_prop))
  
  example.df$demo <- example.df[[d]]
  temp <- example.df %>% group_by(demo, answer) %>%
    summarise(n = n()) %>%
    group_by(demo) %>%
    mutate(prop = n/sum(n), num=sum(n)) %>%
    filter(answer==1 & num > 5) %>% select(demo, prop) %>% rename(raw=prop) %>% 
  left_join(post, by="demo") %>%
  arrange(lm) %>%
  melt(id.vars="demo") 
  
  p <- ggplot(data=temp, aes(x=factor(demo, level=unique(demo)), y=value, color=variable)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line(data=temp[!is.na(temp$value),], aes(group=variable)) +
    ylim(c(0, 1)) +
    ggtitle(paste0(d, ", ", label, ", ", game))
  return(p)
}

plot.post("gender")

1.1.2 Post-stratified on all labels and all games

# Here we make the df that includes game, country, ageCut, gender, label, post-stratified results
# meaning that we are doing the same process for all the labels (more than just stylized) and games (more than just GTA)
games <- unique(long.df$game)
labels <- c("pacifist", "made.for.kids", "cozy", "zen", "fantasy", "space", "heroic", "real.world", "violent", "action", "emotional", "comedic", "experimental", "strategy", "grinding", "anime", "hand.drawn", "stylized", "action.motivation", "social", "mastery", "achievement", "immersion", "creativity")
final.df <- data.frame(label=c(), country=c(), game=c(), raw=c(), lm=c())
ground.truth <- read.ground.truth()

for(label in labels) {
  for(game in games) {
    temp.newdata <- ground.truth
    label.df <- long.df %>% filter(label=={{label}} & game=={{game}}) 
    label.df <- label.df %>% group_by(country) %>% mutate(num=n()) %>% filter(num > 5) %>% ungroup()
    model <- glmer(answer ~ gender + ageCut + (1|country), data = label.df, family=binomial(link="logit"))
    
    # predict with the model
    temp.newdata$country[which(!(temp.newdata$country %in% unique(label.df$country)))] <- NA 
    temp.newdata$estimate <- model %>% predict(newdata = temp.newdata, type="response", allow.new.levels=TRUE)
    
    # post-stratify based on countries
    temp.newdata <- temp.newdata %>% 
      mutate(predict_prop=estimate*UserCount.per) %>%
      group_by(country) %>%
      summarise(lm=sum(predict_prop))
    
    output <- label.df %>% # raw numbers
      group_by(country, answer) %>%
      summarise(n=n()) %>%
      group_by(country) %>%
      mutate(prop = n/sum(n), num=sum(n)) %>%
      filter(answer==1 & num > 5) %>% select(country, prop) %>% rename(raw=prop) %>% # include a participant limit
      left_join(
        temp.newdata, by="country"
      ) %>% arrange(lm)
    output$game <- game
    output$label <- label
    final.df <- rbind(output, final.df)
  }
}

2 Why do we see big differences specific to country/language? Deep dive on Fig 2 country panel

2.1 Thought 1: has to do with culture. (Figure 3)

We find that these differences are closely related to cultural similarity, as quantified by Hofstede similarity

# 1. Find the pairwise correlation between countries based on the Hofstede's framework
# correlation based on six metrics: power.distance, individualism, masculinity, uncertainty
# long.term.orientation, and indulgence
hofstedeDf <- read.csv("hoftstede.csv")
hofstedeDf <- hofstedeDf %>% select(-X) %>%
  mutate(power.distance = power.distance / 100,
         individualism = individualism / 100,
         masculinity = masculinity / 100,
         uncertainty = uncertainty / 100, 
         long.term.orientation = long.term.orientation / 100,
         indulgence = indulgence / 100)  # scale the hofstede score to 0 - 1
corrMatrix <- cor(t(hofstedeDf[, -1]), use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method="pearson")  # remove the first column with countries

corrMatrix[upper.tri(corrMatrix, diag = TRUE)] <- NA
rownames(corrMatrix) <- colnames(corrMatrix) <- hofstedeDf$country
corrMatrix <- na.omit(reshape::melt(t(corrMatrix)))
corrMatrix <- corrMatrix[ order(corrMatrix$X1, corrMatrix$X2), ]
hofstedeCorr <- corrMatrix %>% select(X1, X2, value) %>% dplyr::rename(countryA=X1, countryB=X2, hofstede.corr=value)
hofstedeCorr$countryA <- as.character(hofstedeCorr$countryA)
hofstedeCorr$countryB <- as.character(hofstedeCorr$countryB)
hofstedeCorr <- transform(hofstedeCorr, countryA = pmin(countryA, countryB), countryB=pmax(countryA, countryB))
# construct 24-d vector for each country
countries <- unique(final.df$country)
output <- data.frame(countryA=c(), countryB=c(), label.corr=c(), label=c())
labelSpace <- data.frame(matrix(ncol=0, nrow=24))

# This step forms a game vector with 24 dimension per label/country with means
for(game in games) {
  labelSpace <- data.frame(matrix(ncol=0, nrow=24))
  
  for(country in countries) {
    v <- c()
    curr.df <- final.df %>% filter(country == {{country}} & game=={{game}})
    alllevs <- expand.grid(label=labels)
    curr.df <- alllevs %>% left_join(curr.df, by="label")
    curr.df$country <- country
    curr.df$game <- game
    v <- c(curr.df$lm)
    labelSpace <- cbind(labelSpace, as.data.frame(v))
    names(labelSpace)[names(labelSpace) == "v"] <- country
  }
  output <- rbind(labelSpace, output)
}

# Create a matrix where columns are countryA, countryB, and label.corr
mx <- cor(labelSpace, use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method="pearson")
mx[upper.tri(mx, diag = TRUE)] <- NA
rownames(mx) <- colnames(mx) 
mx <- na.omit(reshape::melt(t(mx)))
mx <- mx[ order(mx$X1, mx$X2), ]
labelCorr <- mx %>% select(X1, X2, value)
labelCorr <- labelCorr %>% dplyr::rename(countryA=X1, countryB=X2, label.corr=value)
labelCorr$countryA <- as.character(labelCorr$countryA)
labelCorr$countryB <- as.character(labelCorr$countryB)
labelCorr <- transform(labelCorr, countryA = pmin(countryA, countryB), countryB=pmax(countryA, countryB))

# Plotting the correlation

ggscatter(combined, x = "hofstede.corr", y = "label.corr", 
          add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE,

          xlab = "Hofstede", ylab = "Genome Label", title="Correlations of Hofstede Pearson and Genome 24d label vector Pearson")

2.2 Thought 2: has to do with translation (Figure 4a)

Culture explains some of country differences, but are we introducing additional bias when looking across languages?

rnormt <- function(n, range, mu, s) {
  if(s == 0) {
    return(c(NaN))
  }
  # range is a vector of two values
  F.a <- pnorm(min(range), mean = mu, sd = s)
  F.b <- pnorm(max(range), mean = mu, sd = s)
  
  u <- runif(n, min = F.a, max = F.b)
  return(qnorm(u, mean = mu, sd = s))
}
# For some weird reason, I need to output the first four variable
compareLanguage <- function(languageA, languageB, inputCountries, label, lower=0, upper=1) {
  languageA 
  languageB
  inputCountries
  label
  
  md <- df
  dfA = md %>% dplyr::filter(label == {{ label }}) %>%  # select the label
    mutate(answer = (1-0) * (answer-lower) / (upper-lower) + 0) %>%  # rescale the Likert scale answer to 0-1 (e.g., 1-3, 1-4 to 0-1)
    dplyr::filter(Language == {{ languageA }} & country %in% inputCountries) %>% 
    group_by(game) %>%
    summarise(mean=mean(answer, na.rm=TRUE), sd=sd(answer, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sd))  # in case there is only one response in a country
  
  # same operation for languageB
  dfB = md %>% dplyr::filter(label == {{ label }}) %>%  # select the label
    mutate(answer = (1-0) * (answer-lower) / (upper-lower) + 0) %>%  # rescale the Likert scale answer to 0-1 (e.g., 1-3, 1-4 to 0-1)
    dplyr::filter(Language == {{ languageB }} & country %in% inputCountries) %>% 
    group_by(game) %>%
    summarise(mean=mean(answer, na.rm=TRUE), sd=sd(answer, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sd))  # in case there is only one response in a country
  
  rnormtA <- c()
  rnormtB <- c()

  for(row in unique(df$game)) {
    meanA <- as.double(dfA[dfA$game == row, "mean"])
    meanB <- as.double(dfB[dfB$game == row, "mean"])
    sdA <- as.double(dfA[dfA$game == row, "sd"])
    sdB <- as.double(dfB[dfB$game == row, "sd"])

    if(any(is.na(meanA)) | any(is.na(meanB))) next;
    if(any(is.na(sdA)) | any(is.na(sdB))) next;
    if(any(sdA == 0) | any(sdB == 0)) next;

    gameA <- rnormt(1000, c(0, 1), meanA, sdA)
    gameB <- rnormt(1000, c(0, 1), meanB, sdB)
    rnormtA <- c(rnormtA, gameA)
    rnormtB <- c(rnormtB, gameB)
  }
  
  # no game is available
  if(length(rnormtA) == 0) {
    return(data.frame(languageA = languageA, languageB = languageB, estimate=NaN, p=NaN, label=label))
  }

  cor.res = cor.test(rnormtA, rnormtB, method=c("pearson"), use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
  return(data.frame(languageA = languageA, languageB = languageB, estimate=cor.res$estimate, p=cor.res$p.value, label=label))
}

matrix <- combn(unique(df$Language), 2)  # get the combination of languages
new.df <- data.frame(languageA=c(), languageB=c(), estimate=c(), p=c(), label=c())
for(col in 1:ncol(matrix)) {
  # for each combination (English vs. language X
  l1 <- matrix[1, col]  # English
  if(l1 != "English") break
  l2 <- matrix[2, col]  # language X
  
  # find the correpondings countries to language X
  language.countries <- df %>% filter(Language == l2)  

  for(label in labels){
    comparison <- compareLanguage(l1, l2, c(unique(language.countries$country)), label, lower=0, upper=1)
    new.df <- rbind(new.df, comparison)  # update the new.df
  }
}

3 How can we use this knowledge to improve upon ML-based recommendation systems? (Case Study 3)

3.1 Consider using a model trained on current homogeneous human labellers all from the same country that does not have English as an official language.

# Using Polish annotator data
# Consider training a model with more diverse (survey-based) training data
ml.df <- long.df %>% filter(label == "stylized") %>% select(Response.ID, game, gender, ageCut, country, answer)
train.3a <- long.df %>% filter(country %in% c("Poland") & labeler == "Yes" & label == "stylized")

3.3 using more diverse survey data

# base model with all the data
set.seed(1)

ml.df <- long.df %>% filter(label == "stylized") %>% select(Response.ID, game, gender, ageCut, country, answer)
ml.df <- ovun.sample(answer ~ game + gender + country, data = ml.df, method = "both", p=0.5,                             N=50000, seed = 1)$data

#create ID column
ml.df$id <- 1:nrow(ml.df)

#use 70% of dataset as training set and 30% as test set 
train <- ml.df %>% dplyr::sample_frac(0.70)
test  <- dplyr::anti_join(ml.df, train, by = 'id')

mod <- glm(answer ~ game + gender, data = train, family=binomial(link="logit"))
test$estimate <- mod %>% predict(newdata = test, type="response")
test <- test %>% mutate(pred.label = ifelse(estimate > 0.7, 1, 0)) %>% mutate(answer=factor(answer), pred.label=factor(pred.label))

confusionMatrix(test$pred.label, test$answer, mode = "everything", positive="1")

# Comparing the three
new.df.3a <- new.df.3a %>% rename(F1.3a = F1) %>% select(-label)
new.df.3b <- new.df.3b %>% rename(F1.3b = F1) %>% select(-label)
new.df.3c <- new.df.3c %>% rename(F1.3c = F1) %>% select(-label)

new.df.3a %>% 
  left_join(new.df.3b, by=c("country2")) %>%
  left_join(new.df.3c, by=c("country2")) %>%
  pivot_longer(c("F1.3a", "F1.3b", "F1.3c"), names_to = "condition", values_to = "F1") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(country2, F1), y=F1, color=condition)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_line(aes(group=condition))+
  ggtitle("F1 scores for all three conditions")
